Day 3 — Operators + User Input
1. Operators in Java

Operators are used to perform operations on variables.

(A) Arithmetic Operators
Operator	Meaning
+	Addition
-	Subtraction
*	Multiplication
/	Division
%	Modulus (remainder)
Example 1
int a = 10;
int b = 3;

System.out.println(a + b);  // 13
System.out.println(a - b);  // 7
System.out.println(a * b);  // 30
System.out.println(a / b);  // 3
System.out.println(a % b);  // 1
Example 2
double x = 5.5;
double y = 2.0;

System.out.println(x / y);  // 2.75
(B) Relational Operators

Used for comparison → result is true/false

Operator	Meaning
==	equal
!=	not equal
>	greater
<	less
>=	greater or equal
<=	less or equal
Example 1
int a = 10;
int b = 20;

System.out.println(a > b);   // false
System.out.println(a < b);   // true
Example 2
System.out.println(10 == 10);  // true
System.out.println(5 != 3);    // true
(C) Logical Operators

Used to combine conditions

Operator	Meaning
&&	AND
	
!	NOT
Example 1
int age = 20;

System.out.println(age > 18 && age < 25); // true
Example 2
int marks = 40;

System.out.println(marks > 35 || marks == 35); // true
2. Taking Input from User

This is where your program becomes interactive.

Use:
Scanner

Example 1 — Integer input
import java.util.Scanner;

public class InputDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int age = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.println("Age is " + age);
    }
}
Example 2 — String input
import java.util.Scanner;

public class InputDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        String name = sc.nextLine();

        System.out.println("Name is " + name);
    }
}
3. Combine Everything
Example 1
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Sum {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int a = sc.nextInt();
        int b = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.println("Sum = " + (a + b));
    }
}
Example 2
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Compare {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int a = sc.nextInt();
        int b = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.println(a > b);
    }
}
4. Common Mistakes (You WILL do these)

Mistake 1 — Forgetting import

Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in); // ERROR

Fix:

import java.util.Scanner;

Mistake 2 — Mixing nextInt and nextLine wrongly
(You’ll face this later, don’t panic)

